                     <h2 class="date-header">February  4, 2010</h2>
                     <div class="entry" id="entry-94">
                        <h3 class="entry-header"><a href="http://wallenberg.stanford.edu/blog/2010/02/more_resources_for_using_twitt.html">More resources for using Twitter in the classroom</a></h3>
                        <div class="entry-content">
                           <div class="entry-body">
                              <p><strong>Tomorrow's Professor Msg.#984 Learning in 140 - Character Bites</strong><br />
<a href="http://cgi.stanford.edu/~dept-ctl/cgi-bin/tomprof/posting.php">http://cgi.stanford.edu/~dept-ctl/cgi-bin/tomprof/posting.php<br />
</a></p>

<p>Once widely dismissed as an instrument of vanity, Twitter is now showing up in serious places. Its citizen-journalistic role after last June's Iranian election was much celebrated; in May, a NASA astronaut became the first to tweet from space ("From orbit: Launch was awesome!!"). Bit by bit, Twitter is finding a role in education.</p>
                              

                              
